replies.bodyText:
The current .NET implementation is on the BlobContainerClient:
        /// <summary>
        /// Restores a previously created container.  The restored container
        /// will be renamed to the name of this <see cref="BlobContainerClient"/>.
        /// If the container associated with this <see cref="BlobContainerClient"/>
        /// already exists, this call will result in a 409 (conflict).
        /// This API is only functional is Container Soft Delete is enabled
        /// for the storage account associated with the container.
        /// </summary>
               public virtual Response Restore(
            string deletedContainerName,
            string deletedContainerVersion,
            CancellationToken cancellationToken = default) {...}

The current user experience for .NET:
BlobContainerClient container = 
    blobServiceClient.GetBlobContainerClient("nameToRestoreContainerTo";
await container.RestoreAsync("deletedContainerName", "deletedContainerVersion");

The restored container will "become" the container associated with this BlobContainerClient, and now users can interact with it via this client.
For the 3 proposed options:
client.createFrom(string deletedContainerName, string deleteContainerVersion) 
I'm not a huge fan of this one.  I'd rather stick with "Restore" in the API name to align with the service.  Also, the name "createFrom"could be confusing to new users who are just trying to create a Container.
client.restore(string deletedVersion)
I could get behind this one.
client.restore(string deletedVersion, string destinationContainerName)
I think this one doesn't align super well with our current user experience.  Currently, a BlobContainerClient only interact with the Container it is associated with.  This would break that convention.
BlobServiceClient.restoreContainer(string deletedContainerName, string deletedContainerVersion)
BlobServiceClient.restoreContainer(string deletedContainerName, string deletedContainerVersion, string destinationContainerName)
These are ok, I'd want restoreContainer to return a BlobContainerClient for convenience.
I prefer the current .NET implementation the most.

In terms of existing APIs and patterns, this feels like a mix of Blob's Undelete and DataLake's Rename operation.
I really like Sean's suggestion because I think that removes all the confusion about how to use the API:
class BlobServiceClient
{
    Response<BlobContainerClient> RestoreContainer(
        string deletedContainerName,
        string deletedContainerVersion,
        string destinationContainerName = null);
}
This doesn't hide the destinationContainerName concept in the BlobContainerClient you use to invoke the API.  Instead it's something you can pass if you want it to change or leave null to keep the same name.

